-- NHL Rangers Win to Retain Eighth Playoff Spot as Jets Keep Pace
-- B y   N a n c y   K e r c h e v a l
-- 2013-04-19T04:48:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-19/nhl-rangers-win-to-retain-eighth-playoff-spot-as-jets-keep-pace.html
The  New York Rangers  and Winnipeg
Jets won last night to stay tied on points in the race for the
National Hockey League Eastern Conference’s final playoff spot.  The Rangers defeated the visiting Florida Panthers 6-1 and
the host Jets kept pace with a 4-3 overtime defeat of the
Carolina Hurricanes.  The Rangers are 22-17-4 for 48 points with five games
remaining in the lockout-shortened season. The Jets are 23-19-2
for 48 points with four games left.  New York  plays at Buffalo
tonight and Winnipeg hosts the  New York Islanders  tomorrow.  Also last night, the Islanders won 5-3 at the  Toronto Maple
Leafs  to improve to 23-16-5. The Islanders, with 51 points, are
in seventh place in the Eastern Conference.  At New York’s Madison Square Garden, the Rangers led 2-0 on
power-play goals by Derick Brassard and Rick Nash before
Jonathan Huberdeau scored for the Panthers late in the first
period.  Mats Zuccarello scored the only goal in the second period
to give the Rangers a 3-1 lead. Zuccarello and Brassard
contributed their second scores of the game in the third period,
with  Brad Richards  completing the scoring.  At Air Canada Centre in Toronto, five goals were scored in
the first period as the Islanders rallied from a 2-0 deficit on
goals by Brad Boyes, Matt Moulson and John Tavares.  Tavares added a second goal 14 minutes, 40 seconds into the
second period and Frans Nielsen made it 5-2 in the third before
Dion Phaneuf got the last goal for the Maple Leafs with 27
seconds remaining.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Nancy Kercheval in Washington at 
